  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2866774005" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2866774005" />
    <a title="Daniel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2404888-daniel"><img alt="Daniel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1559046030p2/2404888.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2866774005?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel" href="/user/show/2404888-daniel">Daniel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780900384035" href="/book/show/1013477.ABC_of_Anarchism">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2866774005" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17930239052520046819">Published in 1929 as “Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism,” Alexander Berkman’s introduction to the principles of anarchist communism is often cited as one of the most accessible introductions to Anarchist thinking. It’s certainly easy-to-read, free of complicated theory and jargon, but I was more puzzled than persuaded by his arguments. The book itself only spends a few chapters discussing the thinking behind anarchist communism proper. The first twenty chapters or so offer a run-of-t</span>
  <span id="freeText17930239052520046819" style="display:none">Published in 1929 as “Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism,” Alexander Berkman’s introduction to the principles of anarchist communism is often cited as one of the most accessible introductions to Anarchist thinking. It’s certainly easy-to-read, free of complicated theory and jargon, but I was more puzzled than persuaded by his arguments. The book itself only spends a few chapters discussing the thinking behind anarchist communism proper. The first twenty chapters or so offer a run-of-the-mill socialist critique of capitalism and the Russian Revolution, which was spoilt by state authoritarianism. Then we get three or four chapters on anarchism proper. Finally, we end with another five chapters on the kind of preparation societies need to begin working toward “revolutionary action.” I’m fine with parts one and three but found myself frustrated with the actual chapters on anarchism proper. I found the reasoning facile and glib, the thoughts of someone who clearly hasn’t tried to think about his subject from another point of view. What I found frustrating about Berkman (mainly popularizer of anarchist theory) is what I find frustrating about his version of anarchism in general. And that’s the simplicity with which anarchists usually dismiss “the state” as an undesirable and entirely malicious institution. For these anarchists, the “state” is simply an unnecessary curb on “liberty,” a means the ruling class uses to suppress its class opponents and to preserve the capitalist economic structures that invest it with its power. The state is the political “face” of a corrupt economic system. The reasoning goes, then, that we’d all be better off if we abolished the state. It’s not that I’m unsympathetic to these claims. Yes, the state curbs our liberty; yes, it is sometimes used as an instrument of class suppression; and yes, it drafts laws that maintains structures of capitalist organization. But I would have liked to see Berkman engage with the vast body of thinking and theorizing that details the very-real benefits a state—even a distinctly imperfect one—can have in the lives of everyday people. There’s no awareness of social contract theory in Berkman or of some of the most compelling justifications of state authority. He complains of curbed liberty without detailing the specific liberties that he is denied. Mill made a compelling proposal in his essay on liberty: he claimed that a state’s authority to curb an individual’s liberty ought to be restricted to those instances where the exercise of that individual’s liberty threatens to endanger another individuals’ liberty or to harm them. The police and the military are the state-backed, tax-funded institutions the state deploys to exert “force.” They have, in Weber’s terminology, a “monopoly on legal repressive force.” No, these instutions are not “perfect” in practice. But it would be highly unrealistic to assume that an efficient police force and military (which are legitimately needed at times) could come about through the kind of voluntary cooperative organizations that Anarchists advocate for. There would need to be a a centralized apparatus or mechanism to oversee the administration of police and military force, and the state is just such an apparatus. I'm inclined to make the same kind of argument about the law and the civil service. There are genuine and legitimate services that the state provides that would be extremely difficult to acquire in a stateless society that depended exclusively on volunteer cooperatives. One needs to remember that the state does not only "strip" people of rights. It also "ensures" that their rights are not violated by others' exertion of their respective rights. Berkman for me exemplifies the kind of pipedream anarchism that refuses to consider the large-scale repercussions of anarchism-in-practice. <br /><br />The anarchist--or Berkman, at least--believes that any kind of state structure will necessarily come to serve interests other than those of the society it ostensibly governs. He is uninterested in "reformism" and transforming state institutions to make them more fair and transparent. He wants, instead, the radical elimination of the state. In getting rid of one evil, it strikes me, he unleashes a pandora's jar of countless others. I prefer Chomsky and Proudon's more nuanced descriptions of the aims and tendencies of anarchism--which don't necessarily amount to the radical and comprehensive abolition of state structures.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17930239052520046819" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

