    <a title="Georgia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/71739177-georgia"><img alt="Georgia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612708651p2/71739177.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3183196396?book_show_action=true">Apr 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Georgia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Georgia" href="/user/show/71739177-georgia">Georgia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/71739177-georgia?shelf=everything-is-politics">everything-is-politics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3183196396" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14815557412665953330">All around a well-rounded introductory read.<br/><br/>This book feels to be - as we all inevitably are - a victim of its time. The nature of the necessity has changed, and so has the character of the working class: building a revolution seems much harder task of radically shifting people&apos;s consciousnesses. There&apos;s also the productivist views on production, mostly aged, if not made obsolete in some parts of the world. The fundamental nature of the matter still stays the same, and I won&apos;t begrudge anyone fo</span>
  <span id="freeText14815557412665953330" style="display:none">All around a well-rounded introductory read.<br /><br />This book feels to be - as we all inevitably are - a victim of its time. The nature of the necessity has changed, and so has the character of the working class: building a revolution seems much harder task of radically shifting people's consciousnesses. There's also the productivist views on production, mostly aged, if not made obsolete in some parts of the world. The fundamental nature of the matter still stays the same, and I won't begrudge anyone for lacking prescience.<br /><br />There's a certain condescension to the Berkman's tone, which - thankfully - mostly disappears in the latter chapters. I don't think it's due to any condescension on Berkman's part, but rather a problem of general voice, but good intentions.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14815557412665953330" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


